.TH CODEX_SANDBOX 1 "July 2026" "codex-cli 0.142.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
codex\-sandbox \- Run commands within a Codex\-provided sandbox
.SH SYNOPSIS
.EX
Usage: codex sandbox [OPTIONS] [COMMAND]...

.EE
.SH DESCRIPTION
Run commands within a Codex\-provided sandbox
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.B [COMMAND]...
Full command args to run under the Linux sandbox
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-c, \-\-config <key=value>
Override a configuration value that would otherwise be loaded from `~/.codex/config.toml`. Use a dotted path (`foo.bar.baz`) to override nested values. The `value` portion is parsed as TOML. If it fails to parse as TOML, the raw string is used as a literal.
.PP
Examples: \- `\-c model="o3"` \- `\-c 'sandbox_permissions=["disk\-full\-read\-access"]'` \- `\-c shell_environment_policy.inherit=all`
.TP
.B \-P, \-\-permissions\-profile <NAME>
Named permissions profile to apply from the active configuration stack
.TP
.B \-\-enable <FEATURE>
Enable a feature (repeatable). Equivalent to `\-c features.<name>=true`
.TP
.B \-p, \-\-profile <CONFIG_PROFILE>
Layer $CODEX_HOME/<name>.config.toml on top of the base user config
.TP
.B \-C, \-\-cd <DIR>
Working directory used for profile resolution and command execution
.TP
.B \-\-disable <FEATURE>
Disable a feature (repeatable). Equivalent to `\-c features.<name>=false`
.TP
.B \-\-include\-managed\-config
Include managed requirements while resolving an explicit permissions profile
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Print help (see a summary with '\-h')
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR codex (1)
